label chapter7:

    # [Scene: Seawall Construction Site | Night]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, insistent percussion with distant brass — tension edged with tired resolve]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls muffled by fog, the whir of drones overhead, the muffled shout of a chant]
    "Narration"
    "You walk up the gravel path with the rest of them, boots clanking, breath visible in the wet air. The construction site is a different world from the boathouse — sterile, engineered, its scale swallowed by"
    "orange floodlight that washes the marsh's soft colors into harsh metal. Concrete smells sharp and new; the air tastes of salt and cooling steam. Every surface seems to carry the echo of heavy machines that will"
    "roll in tomorrow."
    "Volunteers fan out like a slow tide. Some carry handmade signs; others cradle coil after coil of chain. You feel the weight of the night in your shoulders, a familiar, physical gravity that steadies rather than"
    "drags. This is what you chose in the daytime of decisions: to make bodies into barricade, to let small hands and older backs become the story that no press release can perfectly edit away."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A low, unified chant rises — "Our marsh, our future" — then falls into rhythmic clapping]
    show mika_tan at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mika_tan "This is where it gets... loud. You okay?"
    show amaya_saito at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_saito "No quieter than the marsh at high tide. We do what we came to do."
    "Narration"
    "You move through the crowd, laying out instructions the way you'd lay out seedlings: precise, patient, expectant. People listen because this is their shore. A thin boy from the school team jokes to cut the tension;"
    "an older fisherwoman keeps tightening a knot, her hands steady in a way you recognize. You look at each face and feel an odd, fierce gratitude—this is not just protest. It's a congregation."

    menu:
        "Lock the volunteers in pairs around the forms":
            "You guide the pairs into place, the chains heavy and ceremonial. The metal bites cold against palms; someone hums an old sea shanty to steady their breath."
        "Let volunteers stand together, ready but unchained":
            "You tell them to keep their feet and signs visible—no metal yet. Their presence still reads like a line in the sand; their faces photograph well, and you can see the cameras recalibrate."
        "Send a small team to interrupt the light rigs":
            "You point to a handful of younger volunteers. They slip toward the periphery, careful and nimble. If the lights falter, the spectacle loses some of its relentlessness."

    # --- merge ---
    "Return to main narrative"
    "Narration"
    "The drones above hum like a low storm, surveillance and news tangled in the same mechanical breath. Cameras on boom mics angle into the crowd; someone from a city outlet pushes through with a reporter's notepad,"
    "voice sharp and curious. You can feel the narrative forming—already shaped by whoever speaks first. That knowledge sits across the front of your mind like a cold plate."
    show maren_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maren_voss "You could have discussed alternatives. You could have asked for a design review."
    "Amaya Saito: (Your chest tightens.) 'We asked. For months. The town asked. The marsh asked.'"

    maren_voss "The sea will not wait for petitions and petitions' ceremonies.' (She steps forward.) 'This project saves homes. It is precise, and it is decisive."
    "Narration"
    "Her voice is steady, practiced; her conviction is a tool. You find your fingers curling around chain links before you know it. Around you, a murmur rises, some of it agreement, some of it the low,"
    "terrified fear of people who have already watched roofs lift into waves in their minds."
    "Narration"
    "Lucas pushes through the crowd with rain in his hair, droplets beading along the silver streak at his temple. He looks the way someone looks when they've been measuring and re-measuring the same problem and then"
    "assigned himself to a moral calculus that alters lives. He comes to you without the formal buffer of titles — goggles pushed back, sleeves damp, toolkit gone but visible in the wear of his jacket."
    hide mika_tan
    show lucas_herrera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lucas_herrera "Amaya.' (He pauses, searching your face.) 'You could get hurt out here."

    amaya_saito "As could the marsh if no one changes how we build for it."

    lucas_herrera "This isn't about building or not building—it's about scale. We can reduce risk for the whole town with this wall. You know that."

    amaya_saito "Reducing risk for some at the expense of irreplaceable tidal systems isn't a solution. It's a transfer."
    "Narration"
    "He looks away, jaw working. The argument that sits between you is older than both of you: the need to protect family and the need to protect place. Both are urgent, both are right, and in"
    "the way their rightness overlaps they cut. You can hear it in the press mics and in Maren's measured replies—the world is a ledger and you and he are imperfect accountants."

    lucas_herrera "I'm trying to fix something before it breaks. I'm—' (He inhales.) 'I'm tired of slow plans that don't move anyone out of harm's way."

    amaya_saito "I'm tired of quick plans that make the harm someone else's future."
    "Narration"
    "His hand finds yours for a breath—an old, private orbit you both used to move in. The touch is quick and complicated; it is neither a surrender nor a truce. It is, like everything tonight, layered."

    menu:
        "Hold his hand a moment longer, then pull him into the front row":
            "You squeeze his fingers, and for a heartbeat you're not engineer and ecologist but the two humans who first watched the marsh tides together. You steer him forward, into the visible center."
        "Step back and keep your focus on the volunteers":
            "You let your fingers go. He reads the withdrawal as an argument not finished; his face tightens, but he doesn't push."

    # --- merge ---
    "Return to main narrative"
    "Narration"

    "A city reporter's voice crescendos that there is a live feed. The chant rises and falls in wave patterns" "Our marsh! Our future!"
    hide amaya_saito
    show elena_cruz at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_cruz "This is bigger than any one meeting,' she says, and her voice has the tired cadence of someone who has mediated too many impossible mornings. 'I need a path that doesn't get everyone hurt."
    hide maren_voss
    show amaya_saito at center:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_saito "This is our path."
    "Narration"
    "Tension thickens into movement. Security begins to approach the chained-form line with practiced care, their radios whispering like insect wings. An officer orders the crowd to disperse; a camera captures the command and a volunteer's defiant stand. The air tastes metallic with fear and pride."
    hide lucas_herrera
    show maren_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maren_voss "Remove yourselves and we can prevent escalation. You are endangering your neighbors' safety."

    amaya_saito "You endangered the marsh the day you decided concrete would speak for our shore."
    "Narration"
    "A judge on an emergency call hears the live feeds and the filings; a clerk's voice is relayed through a phone in Elena's hand. You don't see the paperwork move, only the tiny, exhilarating eruption of"
    "the crowd when Elena lifts a finger—an injunction, temporary, a bureaucratic wedge. For a brief, euphoric second the site responds like a breath held in relief: the machines idle, security eases restraint, and people hug wet"
    "shoulders with shaky laughter."

    "Mika (shouting, exuberant)" "We did it! We did it—look at them, they're—"
    "Amaya Saito: (You laugh because the sound leaks out, because the world can still make room for a small, public win.)"
    "Narration"
    "The high is sudden and clean. You plant a hand on the cold concrete and let the truth of having stopped a machine for a night go through your bones. The cameras drink it in. The town is awake and visible on screens that pulse across the shoreline's dark."
    "But under the relief is a brittle edge. You feel it in the way security officers are not leaving the perimeter so much as rearranging their positions, in the quiet call that slides under Elena's breath."
    "The cameras that cheered you will also show a narrative that can be twisted: obstructionists standing in the way of progress. A corporate legal team can turn empathy into nuisance with the right filings. Engineers can"
    "accelerate off-camera. You have made a scene; scenes beget responses."
    "Narration"
    "Lucas stands close, rain beading down his lashes. He looks at the concrete as if he sees future stress tests written into its face. There is fatigue in him you didn't see in the daylight of planning sessions."
    hide elena_cruz
    show lucas_herrera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    lucas_herrera "You gave everyone a reason to see us as a problem."

    amaya_saito "We gave them a reason to see the marsh as something worth fighting for."
    "Narration"
    "Elena speaks again, low enough that only you and those beside you hear."
    hide amaya_saito
    show elena_cruz at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_cruz "I have to hold the town together, Amaya. This injunction buys time, but it buys nothing if it tears the council apart. I'm being pulled from every side. I promised to protect homes and livelihoods—I'm trying to keep faith with both promises."
    hide maren_voss
    show amaya_saito at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_saito "Then let's use this time."
    "Narration"
    "As the crowd disperses, clusters form to plan the next steps. Someone pins a note to a board with a map of legal contacts. An older volunteer wraps a scarf around Mika as if trying to"
    "stitch warmth into courage. Phones glow with messages — offers of support, threats, viral commentary. The temporary victory is loud and ephemeral."
    "Your clothes smell of salt and concrete dust. The chain has left a raw print along your wrist that will sting tomorrow. Your chest thuds in a rhythm that is more exhaustion than triumph. For the"
    "first time since you walked up the path, you allow the real, blunt possibility to unspool in your head: the blockade has closed some doors. Certain kinds of negotiation—quiet conversations in well-lit conference rooms where engineers"
    "refine blueprints—are now inflected with the language of obstruction. Headlines will pick the simplest frames. Investors will hear 'delays' and move numbers where they can be less generous. Legal teams will sharpen pencils on clauses."
    "And yet—there is also a widening. The world saw bodies tonight. The town watched itself cohere. For someone you do not know, on a screen far away, the marsh's name might now stick. Those are both true, and that contradiction sits heavy in your bones."
    "Narration (closing page-turn)"
    "You stand in salt-stiff clothes, heart pounding, watching the floodlights recede into cool distance and the marsh reassert its softer textures under fog. The victory tastes of adrenaline and old fishing salt and a new awareness"
    "that the fight has deepened; the path forward will require more than courage and chants. It will require endurance, legal minds, alliances built in the quiet places you may now find barred. You let that sink"
    "in, the brittle victory and the widening world, and breathe the cold, damp air as if it might steady you for what comes next."
    hide lucas_herrera
    hide elena_cruz
    hide amaya_saito

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
